<section xml:id="zeroes-denominator-rational">
    <title>Zeroes of the Denominator</title>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-domains-rational">
        <title>Domains of Rational Functions</title>
        <theorem>
            <title>The Domain of a Rational Function</title>            
<statement>
    <p>
        The <term>domain</term> of a rational function <m>r(x)</m> are all values of <m>x</m> except those that make the denominator equal to zero before canceling any common factors. 
    </p>
</statement>
        </theorem>
        <example>
            <title>Finding the Domain</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Determine the domain of the function <m>r(x)=\dfrac{x^2-4}{x^2-1}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>(-\infty, -1) \cup (-1, 1) \cup (1, \infty)</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>To find the domain, we need to identify the values of <m>x</m> that make the denominator equal to zero.
                  To do this, we factor the denominator as follows:
                <md>
                  <mrow>r(x)=\dfrac{x^2-4}{x^2-1}\\</mrow>
                  <mrow>=\dfrac{x^2-4}{(x-1)(x+1)}</mrow>
                </md>
                By the Factor Theorem, the linear factors of the denominator correspond to values of <m>x</m> that make the denominator equal to zero.
                  Thus, the domain is all real numbers except <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=-1</m>.</p>
                  <p>In interval notation, the domain is <m>(-\infty, -1) \cup (-1, 1) \cup (1, \infty)</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <title>Finding the Domain</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Determine the domain of the function <m>r(x)=\dfrac{x^2-4}{x^2-5x+6}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p><m>(-\infty, 2) \cup (2, 3) \cup (3, \infty)</m></p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
                <p>To find the domain, we need to identify the values of <m>x</m> that make the denominator equal to zero.
                  To do this, we factor the denominator as follows:
                <md>
                  <mrow>r(x)=\dfrac{x^2-4}{x^2-5x+6}\\</mrow>
                  <mrow>=\dfrac{(x-2)(x+2)}{(x-2)(x-3)}</mrow>
                </md>
                While it is tempting to cancel off the common factor of <m>x-2</m>, this will obscure the fact that <m>x=2</m> makes the denominator equal to zero in the original equation. 
                We must not perform the cancellation until we determine the domain</p>
                  <p>By the Factor Theorem, the linear factors of the denominator correspond to values of <m>x</m> that make the denominator equal to zero.
                  Thus, the domain is all real numbers except <m>x=2</m> and <m>x=3</m>.</p>
                  <p>In interval notation, the domain is <m>(-\infty, 2) \cup (2, 3) \cup (3, \infty)</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <note>
      <title>Cancellations and Domain</title>
        <p>If we wanted to graph the previous example, we will need to perform the cancellation at some point to continue the graphing process. How do keep track of the domain in this case without explicitly writing down the entire domain in interval notation?</p>
        <p>When we perform the cancellation, we can write the condition that <m>x \neq 2</m> next to the simplified version of the function to remind ourselves that <m>x=2</m> is not in the domain. The following calculation shows us how to do this:
       <md>
                  <mrow>r(x)=\dfrac{x^2-4}{x^2-5x+6}\\</mrow>
                  <mrow>=\dfrac{(x-2)(x+2)}{(x-2)(x-3)}\\</mrow>
                  <mrow>=\dfrac{x+2}{x-3}, \quad x \neq 2</mrow>
                </md>
                This leads us to an important idea for graphing rational functions: the graph of a rational function is the same as its simplified version but with holes or asymptotes whenever we cancel off linear factors. We'll explore this idea in more detail shortly.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-domains-and-cancellations">
          <caption>The graph of <m>r(x)=\dfrac{x^2-4}{x^2-5x+6}</m> and <m>f(x)=\dfrac{x+2}{x-3}</m> are identical except for a hole at <m>x=2</m>.</caption>
        <sidebyside>
          <figure>
            <caption>The graph of <m>r(x)=\dfrac{x^2-4}{x^2-5x+6}</m></caption>
            <image source="chapter-6/domain_simplified_rational_function.png" decorative="yes" width="20%"/>
          </figure>
          <figure>
            <caption>The graph of <m>f(x)=\dfrac{x+2}{x-3}</m></caption>
            <image source="chapter-6/domain_rational_function.png" decorative="yes" width="20%"/>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
        </figure>
        </note>
    </subsection>
